  "text": "common Salmonella serotypes reported, [5, [CITATION_1] , and although rates of notification are not as high as those for S. Typhimurium, concerns regarding its emergence in Australia make it a priority for epidemiological surveillance. The majority of S. Enteritidis cases in Australia are associated with travel, and nationally only approximately 10% are thought to be locally acquired [CITATION_2] . However, in QLD the number of locally acquired infections is the highest in Australia, and the relative proportion of locally acquired infections compared to overseas acquired infections is greater than the national average and that of other states at 20% [CITATION_3] . Prior to this study, molecular surveillance has not been performed on S. Enteritidis cases isolated in Queensland and local sources of infection are unclear.",
